I'm Chris Herbert.
I'm the managing director\nof the Joint Center
for Housing Studies.
And on behalf of\nthe Joint Center,
it's my privilege to welcome\ndistinguished faculty
and guests, students, and the\nbroader Cambridge community
to the 18th John\nT. Dunlop lecture.
Each year, the Dunlop\nlecture provides us
with an opportunity\nto recall and pay
tribute to Professor Dunlop\nfor his many important
contributions to the worlds of\nacademia, policy, and industry.
John was a remarkable\nman, marked
by a tremendous intellect,\na shrewd vision,
unflagging energy, and an\nimpatience to get things done,
which I experienced a\nbit as a grad student
watching him deal with Jim\nBrown of the Joint Center.
He applied these skills in a\nlong and distinguished career
over the span of many decades as\na scholar, a dean, a mediator,
a labor secretary,\nand an advisor
to presidents of both\nthe US and of Harvard.
But among his many\naccomplishments,
Professor Dunlop was\nalso instrumental
in providing support and\nguidance for the Joint Center
from its founding in\n1959 through the end
of his life in 2003.
Professor Dunlop\nrecognized the importance
of having a center at Harvard\nthat keeps a consistent focus
on housing, given\nthe fundamental role
that decent, affordable\nhomes play as a foundation
for the well-being of\nfamilies and individuals,
as a critical element of\nhealthy and vital communities,
and as an engine\nof economic growth.
It's not an exaggeration to say\nthat without Professor Dunlop's
unwavering vision and\npersistent efforts on behalf
of the center, we probably\nwouldn't be here today.
And so this lecture is a\nsmall but important way
of marking our gratitude\nfor all that he
did to help the center pursue\nour mission of advancing
the understanding of\nhousing and forming policy
and training the next\ngeneration of housing leaders.
Over its history,\nthe Dunlop lecture
has featured a variety\nof perspectives
on critical housing\nissues, offering
a platform for distinguished\nleaders from academia,
from homebuilding, from finance,\nfrom advocacy, and policy.
And looking over the\nlist of past lectures
provides a portrait\nof the housing issues
that have been most\nsalient since the start
of this century, when\nthe lecture series began.
And while the housing\nchallenges facing
the country are\nunfortunately numerous,
in planning this year's\nlecture, the choice
of theme to\nhighlight was obvious
given the timing of\nthe lecture, which
coincides with the anniversary\nof the enactment of the Fair
Housing Act, signed into law\nexactly 50 years ago tomorrow
by President Lyndon Johnson\non April 11, 1968, one
week after Martin Luther King\nJr. was killed in Memphis.
Over the last\nhalf-century, there's
been some progress\nin breaking down
barriers to more integrated\ncommunities, as evidenced
by what could be described as\nmodest declines in segregation
across much of the country.
But nonetheless, racial\nand ethnic segregation
remains quite high,\nparticularly in urban areas
in the Northeast and Midwest.
And importantly,\nsegregation is associated
with a significant\nconcentration of poor minorities
in areas of\nconcentrated poverty.
A growing body of\nsocial science research
has found that these patterns\nhave significant repercussions
for the well-being\nand life chances
of those who live in\nthese communities.
In addition, there's\ngood evidence
that a lack of\ninteraction between
racial and ethnic\ngroups contributes
to prejudice and mistrust.
In short, segregation\nmatters for individuals
affected by this and\nfor the broader society.
However, the forces\nproducing segregation
by race and ethnicity and income\nare arguably different today
than they were 50 years ago.
As studies by HUD have\nfound, overt discrimination
is much less evident.
But the historical legacy\nof past discrimination
lives on in today's\nresidential patterns,
in economic inequality,\nand how choices
are made about where to live.
As a result, if we're to\nhave meaningful improvement
in reducing segregation,\nit'll take more
than simply removing\ndiscriminatory barriers.
It will require\naffirmative steps
to promote integration, which is\nsomething the Fair Housing Act
itself recognized when\nenacted 50 years ago.
So as we considered\nwho to invite
to reflect on the past,\nthe present, and the future
of fair housing, our\nthoughts turned immediately
to Raphael Bostic, president\nof the Federal Reserve
Bank of Atlanta.
Raphael's an obvious choice\nto deliver the Dunlop lecture
in part because his own career\nmirrors Professor Dunlop's
distinguished contributions to\nthe worlds of academia, policy,
and practice.
Until his appointment last year\nas president of the Atlanta
Fed, Raphael was Judith\nand John Bedrosian Chair
in Governance and\nPublic Enterprise
at the Sol Price School of\nPublic Policy at the University
of Southern California.
He's also a Harvard\nundergrad, so we probably
like to take credit\nfor everything
he's done since then.
Through his academic\ncareer, his research
has spanned many fields,\nincluding homeownership,
housing finance, neighborhood\nchange, and the roles
of institutions in shaping\npolicy effectiveness,
all of which have\nstrong connections
to the questions related to\nfair housing and integration.
He also served as Assistant\nSecretary to Policy Development
and Research at HUD\nunder Shaun Donovan,
who we're very pleased to have\nwith us here tonight, as well,
an old friend and a\nJoint Center alum.
And importantly, while serving\nas assistant secretary,
Raphael played a key role\nin developing regulations
for communities receiving HUD\nfunding regarding steps needed
to make good on the Fair\nHousing Act's mandate
to firmly further fair housing.
And in his leadership role\nnow at the Atlanta Fed,
which includes serving on the\nFederal Open Market Committee,
he now wields\nsignificant influence
over the direction of\nfederal financial policy
and how it can serve all\nthe nation's communities.
And for those of us who\nknow him and his work,
we're grateful to have\nsomeone of his intellect,
his perspective, and his\njudgment in that role.
There's no doubt that\nProfessor Dunlop would
have been tremendously\ngratified to have President
Bostic delivering\ntoday's lecture
to help remember his\nlegacy and to speak to such
an important policy issue.
So it's with great honor and\npleasure I introduce to you
Raphael Bostic to deliver\nthis year's lecture.
