So tonight, my topic\nis fair housing.
It's something that I have\nworked on for a while.
And most notably,\nin recent years,
I spent a fair amount\nof time working
on the reform of the\nAffirmatively Furthering Fair
Housing rule.
I'm going to talk a bit more\nabout that in a little bit.
But I've also been involved\nin some of the enforcement
activities, as well.
So Fair Housing Act\nstarted in 1968.
It really was an outgrowth of\na lot of civil rights energy
and activity.
And it's not an accident\nthat it passed on April 11.
This was a direct response\nto the assassination
of Martin Luther King,\nJr. And that impetus
was actually quite\nimportant, getting us
over the finish line.
Now, it was necessary because\nmarkets were not working,
and free markets\nwere not working
for a large number of people.
And the act really charged\nHUD, the new Department
of Housing and\nUrban Development,
with taking a\nleading role to try
to get markets to work a\nlittle better, get housing
to be more accessible\nand more easily attained
for the full range of\nthe American public.
It charged HUD with\ndoing two things.
First was affirmatively\nfurthering fair housing,
and the second was\neliminating discrimination
by enforcing\nanti-discrimination laws.
And it's an interesting and\nimportant juxtaposition.
One was the enforcement.
We were trying to\nstop activities
from happening that\nwere preventing people
to have access.
But the other was actually\nto be affirmative,
to be positive in the\nspace and to take actions
to make sure and ensure\nthat every American had
true access to\nsafe, high-quality,
and affordable housing.
And so today, what\nI want to do is
spend a fair amount\nof time talking
about how we've done\nin both those spaces,
how have we done where\nenforcement is concerned,
and then what's happening\non the affirmative side.
And I do think that\nit's important for me--
Shawn asked me to do this\naffirmatively furthering thing,
and I didn't really understand\nwhat I was getting into.
It was quite a wrestling\nmatch inside the building
because affirmatively\nacting is inherently
a non-compliant activity.
You're trying to get\npeople to do things
because they want to do it.
If you drag people into things\nand you force them to do it,
which is an enforcement\nmindset, they're
going to ultimately\nwant to do less.
They want to engage\nless, and you're
going to make less progress.
So this second\npiece is something
that is quite important as we\nthink about making progress
in basically all of our\ndiscrimination and equal access
issues.
