So it worked.
All right.
So the goal of fair\nhousing is equal access
to economic opportunity.
That's another way to say\nmaximizing the potential
for economic mobility.
And that was actually quite\ninnovative and revolutionary.
I can't take credit for it.
That was written, and it was\nin long before I got there.
But I was put in\nthe place of trying
to convince everyone that we\nwere really going to do this.
And so I can't say it was\nfun, but it was a learning
experience in a lot of ways.
A second thing that emerged\nfrom this new framework
was a focus on racially and\nethnically concentrated areas
of poverty.
And one of the\nthings that we wanted
to do as part of\nthe rule was really
try to give some guideposts\nas to what the most
important problems were, that if\nyou had these kind of problems,
then these are things you\nshould really pay attention
to because in\nprevious iterations,
there was not really a lot of\ndiscussion about what the most
pernicious issues were.
We pointed to this because\nthere's a huge body of evidence
which shows that those\nconcentrations of poverty
are a big problem in\nand of themselves.
You think about the large public\nhousing projects and the issues
that emerged out of that.
And then you overlay\nrace on top of that,
and it's sort of a double\ndoozy until those places become
extremely costly,\nextremely isolated,
and they impose extra\ncosts on society.
So we wanted to call\nthat out and really start
to socialize everyone\non the ideas of how
we are distributing our people\nhas real implications for how
well we're going to work.
And to the extent that we can\nget people to understand that,
that's important.
A third innovation\nthat we started
to put in place\nthrough the new format
was to try to have HUD\nbe viewed as a partner
at the local level.
Now, I talked about enforcement\nand affirmatively furthering.
HUD got the enforcement down,\nand many local communities
didn't like to talk to HUD\nbecause the only conversations
that they ever had were\nin the context of you're
not doing something right.
We're going to sanction you.
We're going to hold your money.
We're going to do all\nthese sorts of things.
And so it was very difficult\nto get many jurisdictions
to want to talk about\nfair housing at all
because in their view, the only\nthing that fair housing did
was bring them\ncloser to a lawsuit,
and they didn't want to do that.
So what we wanted\nto try to emphasize
is that we have as a mandate to\nhelp you affirmatively further.
So we want to be helpful as\nopposed to rapping people
on their knuckles with a ruler.
The fourth innovation,\nwhich I think
is perhaps going to be the\nmost important of all of these,
is the introduction of\na new geospatial tool.
So I'm expecting\nmany of you have
been to a planning commission\nmeeting or a city council
meeting where you've seen a\nbusiness representative get up
with a table of data and\nstart dazzling people.
And the community is at a loss.
They don't have the same\namount of information,
so the conversation\nis imbalanced.
It's out of balance at\ndecision making times.
So what we wanted to do and\ndid quite effectively was say,
OK, we're going to\ndemocratize data.
We're going make it\neasy for everybody
to do the same analyses so\nthat when someone gets up
and they present their\ndata, you can get up
and present the data\nin a different way
to make a different point and\nhave the conversation really
get to a place where we weren't\ndebating about the data,
and everyone had the same data.
So it was a level playing\nfield so that there
can be a shared and unified\nappreciation for what
the challenges are in\nthe local community.
And then the fifth\ninnovation was a new tool.
So we replaced the\nAI with something
we called an "assessment\nof fair housing."
And the assessment of fair\nhousing had a lot of elements.
So I know there are a lot of\nwords on this table, so don't
read the words.
Just know that the fact that\nthere are a lot of words
should be instructive, in the\nsense that our initial goal was
to try to make this as simple\nas possible for jurisdictions.
We have six areas.
The summary is long.
The data analysis is long.
The assessment of\nthe issues is long.
So we wound up\ncreating something
that I think touched on all\nthe elements that we think
are important but in a\nway that ultimately I
think was not as user-friendly\nas we might have hoped.
What we were hoping for was that\njurisdictions would actually
do this on their own.
So in the AI world, what\ntypically happened was
your years came up.
You knew you had to do an AI.
You put out a contract.
You hired a consultant.
They did the whole thing.
They knew what the\nstandard was, and they
would come to the city council.
Maybe they'd read it.
Maybe they wouldn't read it.
But they knew they had to\nget it in, so they got it in.
And we wanted to change that.
We wanted to have fair\nhousing be something
that was understood and\nembraced and wrestled
with by all members\nof the community.
So our goal was really\nto have a product that
was easy to do because that\nease would then mean that people
would not be afraid.
They wouldn't be intimidated,\nand they could instead really
go to the meetings and\ntalk to people about things
that are really important.
All right.
So that was the framework.
That was sort of the innovation.
Now, in our chapter,\nwe talked about what
are the risks for this working.
And if this framework is\ngoing to work, what will we
need to see to have this work?
And we identified eight areas\nthat would be important.
Now, I want to talk\nthrough the eight,
and then I'll talk\nabout how we're doing
in each of these categories.
So the first is that HUD must\nhave sufficient capacity.
So in order to do this, this is\nactually a change in approach.
We wanted to make HUD\naccountable to itself
and to jurisdictions.
So that would mean that\nwhen the AFHs came in,
they actually had to\nbe read and reviewed.
And a decision needed to be\nmade in a fixed amount of time
so this wasn't hanging\nout there over the head
of a jurisdiction.
There needed to be\nopportunities for jurisdictions
to ask questions and\nto talk with people
and to bounce ideas off of\nthem and to understand what
the department was thinking.
And this was just\ngoing to change really
in a fundamental way the\nallocation of resources
inside HUD.
And so HUD needed\nto make sure it
had the capacity to\ndeliver on all the demands
that we were putting on it.
The second is that HUD had to\nhelp increase local capacity.
So in many local\ngovernments, they
don't have a lot of resources.
They're not in a position to\ntake on a new responsibility.
And if we're really serious\nabout having them do it,
we need to put resources in\nplace to make it easy for them.
And so HUD needed to do that\nby either doing it themselves,
developing courses,\nproviding guidance, or hiring
intermediaries to\nprovide those services.
The third is the\nprinciple of local primacy
must be honored and respected.
The one thing that\njurisdictions worried about more
than anything else\nin this framework
was that the federal\ngovernment was
going to tell them what\nto do, that no matter
what they thought\nwas a good idea,
there was going to be\nsome bureaucrat that
was going to come to\ntown and say, oh no,
this is the right answer.
And there would be no\nnotion that their experience
and their time and their\nknowledge of their community
would be able to credibly\nbe brought to bear.
And so we told our staff\nrepeatedly, if there is a plan
and it's credible and we're\nlooking to argue about
whether it's credible or not,\nwe're going with the plan
because we need to have\nlocals believe that they
get to use their\nbrains to figure out
what a good approach\nand good strategy is.
And if there's participation at\nthe community level in the way
that we expect, it should\nbe a collective decision.
This won't be two people in\na room making a decision.
So we should honor that\ncollective very significantly.
The third is that if\nwe're going to have
the principle of local\nprimacy, then the locals
have got to really take it\nseriously and do it well.
They've got to send\ntheir staff to meetings.
They've got to have\nmeetings with communities.
They've got to produce the\ndata and wrestle with it
and work and really have\na good faith effort.
And I will tell you that\ninside of the building
when I was at HUD, this\nwas one that HUD people had
a big problem with.
They did not actually believe\nthat most jurisdictions would
put a good faith\neffort together.
The way I describe\nis there are really
three types of\njurisdictions notionally.
There are the ones who\nare the super achievers.
They want to do\neverything great.
So they're going to\ntake this, and they're
going to do it excellently.
Then there are going\nto be the folks that
aren't going to do this\nunder any circumstances.
They don't believe in this,\nand they're going to say,
I'm not going to advance for\nhousing because I'm against it.
And then there's\neveryone else, the people
in the middle who they don't\nfeel that strongly about it.
But they're not going to go\nright out in front of it.
And the debate and what we\nall have to ask ourselves
is, what's the distribution\nof cities across those three
categories?
Is it that most are\nin the bad category?
Is it most are in\nthe good category?
Is it mostly in the middle?
And your prior about what the\ndistribution of communities is
has a real implication\nfor how you
want to design the regulation.
If you think\neveryone's a bad actor,
then you want to be\nmuch more prescriptive.
You want to be much more\nin an enforcement space
to make people do things.
But if you think everyone\nis in the good side,
then you just need to be\nsubjective and throw up
some ideas, and\nthey'll get it done.
And so we had a lot\nof debate about this.
And people were colored\nfrom their experiences
in enforcement activities,\nin fair housing activities,
and just general\nconversation, the conferences,
about what that answer was.
And that issue became\na huge barrier for us
in building consensus\ninstitutionally.
The fifth area is attention\nhas to be regional,
and we've got to\ngo beyond housing.
So I've talked a lot about\nthe go beyond housing already.
The regional is important\nbecause ultimately, economies
don't respect\njurisdictional boundaries.
And all of our metro areas\nare economic engines,
fundamentally.
They produce things, and we come\ntogether to do those things.
And so if you think at a very\njurisdictional level, the job
location or the school that you\nwant to access or the training
program, if it's not\nin your jurisdiction,
then it's outside\nof your purview.
So only by thinking regionally,\nby thinking collectively
about where are all\nof our amenities,
can we get a plan that's\nlikely to be positive in all
those dimensions.
And so the regional aspect\nwas actually quite important.
The data must be leveraged\nto give everyone a voice.
So we really wanted to make\nsure that this data tool got
in the hands of\nregular people and got
in the hands of newspaper\nreporters and people
outside of the usual\nprocess to try to say,
OK, you have as much\ninformation as everybody else.
You should not be intimidated\nto go to these meetings.
You should not be intimidated\nto have an opinion.
And if you do that, then\nthe community will be
your community as well\nas everybody else's.
That's a very important\nmessage that I
don't think many had\nheard very often,
and we hadn't really\ngiven them tools
to have a hope of\nreally believing that.
The next to last one's\nfoundations and nonprofits.
They've got to monitor\nand be partners,
be partners with the communities\nbut also be partners with HUD.
And in many instances,\nparticularly
in the nonprofit space,\nthey were adversaries.
They spent most of their\ntime arguing and fighting
with each other to try to get\na few extra resources here
and there, and those are\nnot constructive contexts
to be doing long-term planning.
You all have had\narguments with people,
and you don't want\nto sit down and then
be nice to them an hour later--
at least, me, an hour.
It takes me a little\nlonger than an hour.
And so if you've had\nyears of bad experiences
or negative,\ncombative experiences,
the idea that all\nof a sudden, you're
all going to get\ntogether has got
to be something that\nhas got to be purposeful
because it's not just\ngoing to happen on its own.
So we needed to have\neveryone position themselves
as partners.
And then the last one is that\nthe political risk must not
be fatal.
At the time we wrote\nthis, there were a number
of proposals in the\nCongress to really gut
the whole notion of the\naffirmative furthering
regulation and,\nas a consequence,
really make it impossible\nto do the things that we had
worked to try to put in place.
So those were the eight\nthings that we called out
as the preconditions for\nsuccess, if you will.
And so the question naturally\nis, where are we today?
And so I have my view,\nand I've put those here.
So the first is I talked about\nHUD having sufficient capacity.
HUD didn't add any capacity.
And in fact, HUD\nwent the other way
and said, because we\ndidn't add any capacity,
we're going to waive everybody.
So no one actually\nhas to do the AFH.
They can go back to the\nAI framework if they want.
So we didn't do very well here.
In terms of the second,\nincreasing local capacity,
I think there has\nbeen progress here.
In the appropriations\nfor the department,
HUD set aside a fair amount\nof money for third parties--
Enterprise Community Partners,\nassociates, and others--
to be available to provide\ntechnical assistance
and training for\nlocal governments.
And some have actually\ntaken advantage of it.
And so I think\nthere's progress here,
and that knowledge that\nthat exists in the space
will not go away.
That expertise will be there.
And so there's an\nopportunity for good things
to happen there.
In terms of principle\nof local primacy,
there's been progress\nhere, as well.
I have to say I'm pleased\nto be able to say this.
Many locals actually stepped\nup with interesting ideas that
may not have\ninitially been viewed
as in the purview of\nfair housing, really,
and HUD let them go\nthrough, which was good.
So example is Los Angeles.
Part of the AFH planning\nprocess resulted
in a new understanding between\nthe police and the transgender
community and how they interact.
There was creativity in terms of\nthe LA Unified School District
and their use of vacant land\nnear high-performing schools.
These are all things that\nwere not really being
suggested in an old framework.
So there was a lot\nof promise that
emerged out of the experience.
The locals must make\na good faith effort.
I think here, there's\nbeen some progress.
It's not as great as\nI would have hoped,
in part, I think,\nbecause of HUD's issues.
So many of the\ncommunities would ask
HUD for technical assistance\nand HUD was actually
quite slow in making those\nresources available, such
that by the time\nthe resources came,
the clock had ticked a lot.
And so we were just in a\nrush to get something in,
which means that the good faith\neffort that we had conceived of
is really going to be cut\nshort pretty considerably.
But I think that\nthat can be remedied.
In terms of the attention\nbeing regional, extending
beyond housing, we saw a\nnumber of jurisdictions
in the early rounds really\nembrace the regional notion.
From Chicago to Denver to New\nYork City, all of these places
were places that\nreally tried to think
about this in a regional way.
And I think they were getting\nit in a pretty significant way.
Very much a significant\namount of progress
in terms of data leveraging--
there is quite a lot\nof infrastructure
that was put in\nplace, and people
made themselves use of it.
One of the things that\nwas learned through some
of the early rounds\nis that for people
who are not used to working\nwith data, who haven't had
the opportunity to wrestle\nwith things and play around,
they need space before\nthe meetings just
to figure out what to do.
So creating opportunities-- and\nthis is a role for foundations,
I think, to provide--
is some safe time and\nspace where they just
come, wrestle with the\ndata, and try to figure out
what it means for themselves.
And so if they can do that,\nwhen the meeting happens
at the community level,\nthey're in a position
to be articulate about\nexactly what they think.
And it should give\nmore confidence
that that voice will\nbe taken seriously,
and I think that's something\nthat we should hope for.
And then in terms of the\nfoundations and nonprofits
being monitors and\npartners, I think
there's been a fair\namount of progress here.
And for me, I talked with some\nfolks who monitored the process
in a number of these cities.
And what they said\nwas they were struck
by how many nonprofits\ncame to the table
believing they understood\nwhat it meant to try
to run a city department.
And then they got in\nthe room and started
making their demands, and the\ncities told them, well, we only
have a third of the money\nthat you think we have.
And those constraints then\nchanged the calculus around
what's possible, how do\nwe do prioritization,
how do we engage long-run, and\nI think it brought the groups
closer together because in many\ninstances, I got a sense that--
actually, I experienced this.
Nonprofits would\ntalk to me and say,
you're just being difficult\nto be difficult. I was like,
no, we're being difficult\nbecause this is hard.
We don't have a lot of\nresources to do these things.
And so we need to\nbe extra creative.
There are many things\nthat seem like good ideas
that we don't have\nthe resources to do.
And by making it\nreal, I think there
was tremendous value in that.
And then the political\nrisk, it remains.
It probably remains\nfor different reasons,
but there are some\nreal challenges
to think about in\nterms of whether
the political\nenvironment that we're in
is going to be conducive to a\nreal embrace of affirmatively
furthering fair housing, of\nbeing positive in fair housing
to try to create equal access to\nopportunity and to communities.
All right.
So that's where we are.
Now, I've already\nsaid I'm pretty
optimistic that many of\nthe elements that we've
put in place can be positive.
I wanted to say a few\nwords on enforcement,
and then I'll wrap up.
So enforcement has always been\na prominent aspect of the act,
and it was trying to\nmake progress where
fair housing is concerned.
Many instances, it\nwas HUD officials
doing the enforcement.
And in many other\ncircumstances, it
was communities and\nnonprofits suing
HUD to do the enforcement.
And at one point,\nwhen we came in,
there were a ton of\noutstanding lawsuits
that had not been resolved.
And with Shaun's leadership,\nwe resolved all of them.
I think by the time we\nwere done, I got to do one.
Was mine the last one?
I think it was close to the end.
So I got a lot of gray hair.
About a third of it was from\nthat working on that project,
but it was because\nin many instances,
these issues are\nchallenging the way
that the HUD programs operate.
HUD is a conduit for resources,\nand then the decisions
get made somewhere else.
And so in that kind of\ndistributed context,
there's a real question\nabout who is accountable
and who should be accountable.
And there's a lot of\nwrestling that happens
within the government\nabout that,
within the courts about\nthat, and among communities.
And many of the\nresolution issues
are really centered on this\nquestion of accountability.
Most recently, there was\nthe disparate impact ruling
that the Supreme\nCourt made in 2015.
This was something\nthat had been I
think long dreaded by the\nfair housing community
and an expectation\nthat this would not
be viewed as positive or\npossible or even legal.
But the Supreme Court found\nsomething quite different,
which was interesting.
I think that it will be\nuseful moving forward
in affecting the types of things\nthat will receive scrutiny
from a practice perspective\nand hopefully will
eliminate a number of the\nbarriers that currently exist.
Now, the last thing\nI wanted to say
is I don't expect\nthat we're going
to see a lot of creativity\non the affirming side,
on the positive side, on\nthe partnership side, given
the steps that we've seen\nin the Department of Housing
and Urban Development\nin the last year or so.
So it may be the case\nthat moving forward,
this is going to be where\na lot of the action is.
And as I said, this\ndoes not make me happy,
in the sense that I'd\nrather have people
do the things because\nthey want to do them,
because they understand the\nvalue in doing them, rather
than dragging them and forcing\nthem to do things because that
creates a relationship that\nis less likely to be positive
and embracing over\nthe longer run.
So if we can try to return\nto some level of balance,
I think we will be\nin a better place.
All right.
So to wrap up, this is\nthe Fair Housing Act.
It's a landmark\npiece of legislation.
Tomorrow, it becomes\n50 years old.
And it really did\ncreate a sea change
in terms of how we should\nthink about housing markets
and what works for\npeople and what
we should expect people\nto experience as they
engage in housing markets.
It has not solved\nall the problems.
We still have a fair\nnumber of problems.
But it did create\na framework that
allowed us to start\nto attack them
and to try to make progress\nand make points that reduce
the number of people\nwho are constrained
in their pursuit of the American\ndream for housing reasons.
There are maybe other issues,\nbut in the housing space,
we definitely have\nmade progress.
I'm actually quite\noptimistic moving forward,
and I would say that\nin today's world,
I think there are\nmany people who
understand that economic\nmobility is at risk.
So I spend a lot of time flying\naround the country talking
to regular people, business\npeople, community folks.
And all of them see\nthe tremendous change
that's happening in the\neconomy and understand
that the expectations about\nwhere they're going to be
and where their\nchildren are going to be
are quite different than\nthey were 20 or 30 years ago.
And so this notion\nthat we should
be trying to do all\nthe things that we
can to maximize the likelihood\nof having every person have
access to economic mobility\nis something that I'm finding
resonates with people.
And so this may be a\ntime to really start
to talk about the notion\nthat fair housing is
just part and parcel of all the\nthings you're thinking about.
And it can be part\nof the solution
as we move forward to make\nsure that the next generation
and the generation after that\nare living in an America that
really does work and provides\naccess to the American dream.
So I will stop there.
And I guess there's\ntime for question,
so I'm happy to do that.
